title: Jonction axe moteur (6mm) / roues de roller (22mm)

description.text:
Lors de mes ateliers robotique, la réalisation des jonctions roue/axe moteur représente souvent une difficulté pour les jeunes.
Voici donc un ensemble de deux pièces pensées pour fixer facilement une roue de roller (ou de trottinette) sur un arbre moteur de 6mm de diamètre.
Aucun réusinage n'est nécessaire : 4 écrous M3 viennent s'intégrer dans le modele pour remplacer les taraudages. N'hésitez pas à me faire part de vos remarques pour améliorer cette pièce !
(première réalisation sous TinkerCad : https://tinkercad.com/things/1gTN3330gnU)

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Insertion des écrous et assemblage Ce modèle est pensé pour intégrer des écrous M3 afin de ne rien devoir tarauder... Vous aurez besoin par moteur de :
  • 4 écrous M3 (3 dans les emplacements hexagonaux et un dans la "fente" pour la vis de pression).
  • 1 vis de pression (sans tête) M3x10
  • 3 vis M3x25 à tête conique
    • Une fois les deux pièces imprimées, intégrez les écrous à l'aide d'une pince et du plan de travail.
    Emboitez la première pièce sur l'arbre moteur (vis de pression face au méplat) puis vissez la vis de pression (M3x10).
    Emboitez ensuite une roue de roller dont vous avez enlevé les roulements (diamètre 22mm) sur la seconde pièce du moyeu.
    Assemblez le tout à l'aide de 3 vis M3x25 à tête conique.

description.text: Iphone amplifier!

This is a Magnetic Camera Mount.
You attach one piece to the tripod and the other to the camera and the two pieces "clip" together. You have to put magnets inside the printed object, as well as a nut, for this to work properly.You have to pause the print, place the magnets (there are "pockets" inside the blocks) and then continue.
I used small magnets with 1mm height and 12mm diameter (that was what I had).
I put 2 magnets in every "pocket". There are 4 pockets on every piece so I used a total of 16 magnets.
The "connection" is not strong enouth to hold my camera vetically (I sould have used stronger magnets). I also uses a bolt and a nut for the top and bottom pieces to attcj to tha camera and tripod. You have to be careful to ensure all the magnets face the same way (polarity) so all the magnets in the bottom part will "attract" the magnets in the top part, to get maximum attraction force.
An other thing to consider is that these small magnets are really stong. My most hotends are aluminum and brass so there is no problem but you have to check if your hotend has any iron parts or you won't be able to print this.
You also have to be very careful when you "place" the magnets because they "jump" and connect with each other. This is a WIP, I will make another version when I get some stronger magnets.
The "target" is to be able to hold my cameras verticaly.

title: Prusa I3 - Z Axis Anti-Backlash Nut with Home Depot Springs

description.text:
This DYI anti-backlash nut design is for printers using 5mm rods.
Also, I only recommended this for printers with Auto Bed Leveling (see rationale under "some background" below as to why) The .STL file has a pair with mirrored versions (one side is thicker to compensate for the thinner wall on side facing the printer part) You will also need:
1) Additional pair of 5mm nuts
2) 1 Spring set from Home Depot (see picture)
3) 4 washers
5) Only if you have an X-Axis belt tensioner: If the belt tensioner is fixed with a Hex Cap M4 screw you may need to replace it with an M4 screw with a Button or round Cap. Id you don't do so the part will bump on the screw. Instructions: 1) Print the 2 parts (mirrored versions)
2) Prepare the part carefully (more instructions below) .
3) Remove your rods, remove the existing 5mm nuts
4) Mount the printed part with the nuts (2 existing from the rod + 2 new), washers, springs
5) Install the part in each rod. This may be also a good opportunity to clean your rods and lubricate as needed.
6) Install the rod with the new part in the printer. The top of the printed part will fit in the printer's 5mm nut catcher - see picture)
4) Rotate both rods by hand to check if they rotate freely after you mount in the printer Some background: Without bed Auto-Leveling repraps using screw rods only move the Z axis upwards layer by layer. In this case gravity keeps the nut siting against the bottom of the thread. With Auto-Leveling the printer will move the Z Axis up and down during print (similar case to CNC machines and Delta printers). If the nut is not running on the thread tightly there is a possibility of introducing a small Z variance due to the tolerances between the nut and the thread. This simple device ensures the nuts are always siting on the thread by pushing two nuts against each other by means of a spring, with a washer interfacing between the spring and the nut.

Part preparation Removing the support from the holes is tricky due to the fact this is a small piece and if you are not careful you may crack it. You will also want a clean removal so that the washer and the nut will sit perfectly. (the .STL has been adjusted so that the nut and the washer will fit comfortably after printing to make the preparation easier) With a very thin plier start by pinching and pulling the supports from holes, then use an allen screw driver or any small cylinder to "punch" the support out. The support should come out clean after some back and forth. You could use a drilling machine rotating really slowly but in my experience this make it more difficult to remove the supports cleanly. You will also need ensure the hex sides of the part that go into the 5mm nut catcher are well finished and flat (you may need some filing or sharp knife finishing). Finally, clean the part from any PLA or ABS debris you that could stick to the rod before installing on the rod. You can wash, blow air, etc..

If you are upgrading your prusa i3 hotend to the E3D V6 or an equivalent hot-end with the standard groove mount, you will need some way of mounting it to your x-carriage. The mount attaches to the x-carriage using the same four hole mounting system that is used on the prusa I3 rework, so you will need to print off a compatible x-carriage. This design uses a clamp so your hotend will stay firmly in place and wont wobble around. This x-carriage comes with support for a cable chain, specifically the one by Rotoscan (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:11978). It also has a cable management hole at the back to manage the cables from your hot-end and fans. This compact stand lifts your laptop up and over your external keyboard, letting you use both in tight spaces.
I'm printing this on a MakerBot Replicator 2X -- when printed on its side, the stand fits in the X and Y dimensions, but I've had to scale Z down, making the stand significantly narrower than my MacBook Pro, but it's still extremely stable.

I wanted a laptop stand that would allow me to use my noisy, awesome IBM Model M keyboard and my MacBook Pro while sitting at the breakfast bar of my kitchen, which is only about eighteen inches deep. To save space, the laptop had to be lifted up and over my keyboard. I started off by modifying yusufk's Angled MacBook Pro Stand, but the model got more and more faceted until I realized it would be simpler to redesign it. This design retains the angle and general shape of his stand, but has a smaller base, two vertical supports instead of just one, I kept the stand completely identical from layer to layer (left to right), letting you scale it to whatever width (Z dimension) your printer can accommodate without making it look weird. I also added a few design flairs! 123D Design makes it very easy to turn edges into curves using the filleting tool under "Modify" -- it's a bit addictive! You can even put curves on your curves, because...never mind. One trick I used to make it easy to experiment was to keep multiple copies of the model -- I kept saving version 1a, 1b, 2a, 2b, 2c, 3a, 3b, etc. This let me come back to revisions where pieces were still movable and reposition, merge, and add curves in different ways.

title: Blower Fan Shroud for PrintrBot Simple 1403

description.text: Finally, a fan shroud for the Printrbot that makes use of the advantages of a blower fan! I love my printer, but have been disappointed by its ability to print overhangs. It traced the reason for this back to the fan, which is a pretty anemic 40mm PC fan, designed for high volume and not pressure. it's good for blowing lots of air into a case, but not very good at pushing it through a small space like a fan shroud. A blower fan like one of these on Amazon can produce much higher air pressure, which should translate to more airflow over the part. So, after some work, I came up with this fan shroud! It positions the fan much closer to the nozzle than the stock cooler, and uses an open, surround-style shroud to get as much air on the print as possible, but also making sure that all sides receive airflow. I've found that other surround-style coolers have very small openings which limit airflow too much, or are too close to the print, this shroud should not have either of those issues. It is also compatible with the fans on the new Ubis hotend and the E3D V6*, and includes a mount for your extruder cables. I've done some simple overhang tests, and while I don't have a "control" for comparison, it is significantly better than my previous prints (I can now go down to 12 degrees or so with no drooping/curling). Results may vary of course, so I'm curious to see how others' pritners perform with it!

• existing fan mount m3 bolts & nuts
  • two 6-32 x 3/4"or m3 x 18mm bolts (or whatever you have that fits, this isn't rocket science :P )
  • a thread tap to match your two bolts.
  • allen wrench/screw driver
    -needle nose pliers or tweezers
    -solder iron/solder or small crimps
    -optional: JST connector, heat shrink tubing.
    • *note: I haven't tested these extruders as I don't own them, I would definitely appreciate anybody who has these installed to try this out and let me know if any issues arise! and if anybody is wondering where I got the lovely fan cover, it's a scaled version of this one by Lemm.

Parametric Hieroglyphic Alphabet. With the openscad program "hieroglyphs_bitmap.scad" it is possible:
  • to draw parametric hieroglyphic texts by use of the function "drawText()"
  • to draw a hieroglyphic text inside a cartouche by use of the function "drawTextInCartouche()"
    • samples: drawText(["A","B","C",0); // text written from left to right
    drawText(["A","B","C",1); // text written from top to bottom drawTextInCartouche(["K","U","F","U"],0); // characters are laying on top of cartouche
    drawTextInCartouche(["K","U","F","U"],1); // characters are carved inward The program uses a 32x32 bitmap to define a single hieroglyphic character. The bitmaps have been generated using the vbscript "ConvertBMP.vbs". This script converts a 32x32 (8 bits color) .bmp file into a textual bitmap that can be used by the openscad file. So if one wants to replace any of the bitmaps currently used the scad file, the new textual bitmaps can be generated using the vbscript. Most important generic parameters:
  • pixelSize = 0.5; // determines the overall size of the character

description.text: These are a set of hinges for the enclosure designed by Mike Kelly. Here: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:681843. These hinges can be installed without drilling any holes in the Robo3d cover. You would thread and install 2 set screws in the 2 holes shown. You slide the hinges onto the case and tighten the set screws. The part of the hinge that goes onto the plexiglass has 2 holes but I found that there was only enough room for 1 flat head screw. If you want to use 2 screws, you would have to make the hinge longer. Or you could use 2 socket heat cap screws. These Things have been updated. The latest update date is 1/13/16. They were made thicker and changed so that the two screw holes on the latch were further apart to put 2 flat head screws in. A drilling jig has been added to assist in drilling the holes in the acrylic. You just place the jig up against the plastic and drill 1 hole. Then put a screw through that hole to hold the jig in place. Then drill the second hole.

description.text: The Fury 250 uses 2 stock base plates and 4 arm pieces from the ZMR 250 with 25mm round standoffs. All other plates are custom. You may 3D print the arms and base plates, though I've found the arms need to be carbon to stand up to racing level crashes. Top plate is designed with a built in section for a Frsky D4R-ii and video transmitter. The video transmitter is house at the rear to allow changing video frequencies easily. I use zip ties to hold the antenna and battery connector. Side panels have 3 raised sections in each hole to improve the fit. Should you find the fit to tight you may wish to drill out the standoff hole with a 1/8" bit, My FPV camera works great without vibrations, though the next version will update the FPV plate to use rubber dampers without screws. Feel free to remix if you have ideas for an FPV plate with rubber dampers. Parts List: http://www.banggood.com/Diatone-M325mm-Aluminum-Standoff-For-ET-180-ET-200-Frame-Kits-20PCS-p-986906.html http://team-legit.com/product/zmr-250-replacement-arms-2-pack/ http://team-legit.com/product/zmr250-bottom-plates-2/

description.text:
New Update 9 Feb 16 I've uploaded my 3rd and (hopefully) final version of this design. I've printed and installed the final version which contains alot of adjustments making things fit together much better. There shouldn't be any need for any kind of post-processing anymore. This finally represents what I imagined a finished product for this to be, I hope it helps you as much as it does me! This is an adaptation for the Hictop Prusa i3 to use the E3D V6 Extruder. This is my first forray into designing parts for my printer. I have already been successfully using a previous version of this setup very successfully and this corrects most of the issues I had with it as well as adds some visual flair. I DO use a piece of PTFE tube from the motor to the E3D. It fits directly in the hole underneath the extruder motor and should be cut flush. title: Kyosho Mini-Z MR-03 Motor Wire Clamp

description.text:
After having a couple of wires snap off the main MR-03VE control board, I set about to finding a better way.   The original factory design has no strain relief for the brushless (or brushed) motor wires.   They tend to flex quite a bit and eventually being such thin wire they will break loose forcing you to disassemble and re-solder them.
This simple clamp prevents the flexing of the motor wires at the main PCB.   Future design will likely incorporate a tie-wrap holder on the top to further help secure the motor wire bundle but this version works great.
You will need a single 2mm screw for the clamp (2x4 should work).

Prints fully assembled in "flat packed" mode (what..the..?) See : http://youtu.be/bl2VTvjv_UA

http://www.gyrobot.co.uk

Print without support, it's all in the geometry.
It prints fully assembled in "flat packed" mode, just open and screw to tree/board.
I have included a PARTITION.stl so you can print two birdhouses off, and attach them back to back, to make a hanging condo.
A really small footprint for a large birdhouse. If you want to push the boundaries of unattended print time then I have included an stl where 3 of these are nested (sorry) together. The total build cube required for a nest of 3 is only = 176mm x 176mm x 107mm.
